<br>
Pros: (1) appears this system could eliminate people voting for a D because they know the G will lose and are afraid voting for G will lead to an R winning the election.  While also not giving them an advantage over the people that rank the R in the top slot.<br>
(2) Because of the above we could begin to see third and fourth party candidates getting into office (yay down with 2 party system).  It would still be a long time before the D's and R's lose there stranglehold but is possibly a step in the right direction.<br>
<br>
Cons: (1) mathematics.  I am not sure many people will be able to understand the math behind this.  For example it probably won't occur to people that ranking 2nd and 3rd choices could actually hurt their 1st choice in a close election.  <br>
(2) Buy in.  Selling this concept to voters probably isn't going to be easy.  It is riddled with things that the average voter won't understand readily.  (I think it could be explained sufficiently to most voters though).<br>
(3)  I really don't have a 3rd con but I am going to look for arguments for and against it.  I am sure someone out there has thought of something I haven't ;-)<br>
