<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>drop the weakest (smallest magnitude) defeat, repeating if necessary until one of the candidates is unbeaten.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If your first choice is ranked lower (Nader), and your second choice is ranked higher in the runnings (Gore), then you've helped bump Nader out of the runnings by making the split between Gore and the other candidates higher. BUT you've also helped Nader more than Gore by giving him am extra vote against everyone else, including Gore.<br>
<br>
Example:<br>
You've voted like this: Nader 1, Gore 2, Bush 3<br>
Total results - an ambiguous vote:<br>
G/B 32   XB/G 20X<br>
N/G 31   XG/N 20X<br>
B/N 30   XN/B 15X<br>
   -You've added one vote to N/G, but you've also added one vote to G/B, keeping the spread between the two elections the same, meaning Gore wins. If you'd have just ranked Nader, and left other slots blank, the race would be even (G/B 31). I'm not sure what they'd do in that situation, but as it stands in this election, Gore wins.<br>
<br>
Of course, this isn't a problem except in the closest races. But say the spread looked like this: <br>
<br>
G/B 32,000 <br>
N/G 31,000. <br>
<br>
If 1,001 people wanted to put down N as their only ranked choice, but didn't realize that NOT doing so would hurt N, then they would have hurt N unknowingly.<br>
<br>
Even with this system, though, they've still had a fair say in the situation, and were responsible for Gore winning the election - a much better choice for them than Bush.<br>
<br>
